│ stop({"edit_points": [[349, 353, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp"]],       │
│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `loop-vectorize` pass is crashing with  │
│ a `SIGABRT` due to a failed assertion: `isa<> used on a null pointer`. This occurs within  │
│ the `VPPartialReductionRecipe::computeCost` function. This function is responsible for     │
│ estimating the cost of a partial reduction operation, which is a key part of vectorizing   │
│ reductions on some architectures like AArch64 with SVE. The assertion failure indicates    │
│ that the cost model is trying to inspect the properties of a recipe that doesn't exist (is │
│ `nullptr`), pointing to a flaw in how the VPlan is constructed or how the cost model       │
│ interprets it.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log is very revealing. The     │
│ crash happens when the vectorizer is calculating the cost for a scalable vectorization     │
│ factor (`VF vscale x 8`).\n\nLooking at the VPlan for this VF, we see a crucial            │
│ detail:\n```\nVPlan 'Initial VPlan for VF={vscale x 8,vscale x 16},UF>=1' {\n...\n<x1>     │
│ vector loop: {\n  vector.body:\n    ...\n    PARTIAL-REDUCE ir<%rdx.next> = add ir<%rdx>,  │
│ ir<%conv1>\n    ...\n}\n...\n}\n```\nThe `PARTIAL-REDUCE` recipe represents the reduction  │
│ operation `add nsw i32 %rdx, %conv1`. Its operands are:\n1.  `ir<%rdx>`: The reduction PHI │
│ node.\n2.  `ir<%conv1>`: The value being added, which is `%conv1 = zext i8 %c to           │
│ i32`.\n\nThe key observation is that `%conv1` is a loop-invariant value defined *outside*  │
│ the loop. In the VPlan representation, such live-in values do not have a \"defining        │
│ recipe\" within the VPlan's loop body.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe crash occurs   │
│ in `VPPartialReductionRecipe::computeCost`. Let's trace the logic with the information     │
│ from our analysis:\n\n1.  The function is called to compute the cost of the                │
│ `PARTIAL-REDUCE` recipe.\n2.  It correctly identifies that the first operand (`ir<%rdx>`)  │
│ is a reduction PHI, so it enters the `else if (isa<VPReductionPHIRecipe>(OpR))` block.\n3. │
│ Inside this block, it attempts to analyze the binary operation of the reduction by getting │
│ the defining recipe of the *second* operand: `auto RedPhiOp1R =                            │
│ getOperand(1)->getDefiningRecipe();`.\n4.  As we established, the second operand is        │
│ `ir<%conv1>`, a loop-invariant live-in. It has no defining recipe within the VPlan's       │
│ context, so `getDefiningRecipe()` correctly returns `nullptr`.\n5.  The code then          │
│ immediately attempts to use this `nullptr` in an `isa<>` check: `if                        │
│ (isa<VPWidenCastRecipe>(RedPhiOp1R))`. This triggers the assertion `Val && \"isa<> used on │
│ a null pointer\"`.\n\nThe fundamental flaw is that the cost model for                      │
│ `VPPartialReductionRecipe` does not account for the possibility that one of its operands   │
│ is a loop-invariant value without a defining recipe. It incorrectly assumes the operand    │
│ will always be defined by another recipe within the plan (like `VPWidenRecipe` or          │
│ `VPWidenCastRecipe`).\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to make the cost      │
│ model robust to `nullptr` recipes for its operands. When the defining recipe is `nullptr`, │
│ it signifies a loop-invariant scalar operand. The cost logic should handle this case       │
│ gracefully.\n\nI will add a null check before the `isa<VPWidenCastRecipe>` call. If        │
│ `RedPhiOp1R` is null, we can simply proceed, as there is no special cost associated with a │
│ pre-existing scalar value.\n\n```patch\n---                                                │
│ a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n+++                                      │
│ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n@@ -346,9 +346,11 @@\n     ExtAType =    │
│ GetExtendKind(OpR);\n   } else if (isa<VPReductionPHIRecipe>(OpR)) {\n     auto RedPhiOp1R │
│ = getOperand(1)->getDefiningRecipe();\n-    if (isa<VPWidenCastRecipe>(RedPhiOp1R)) {\n-   │
│ InputTypeA = Ctx.Types.inferScalarType(RedPhiOp1R->getOperand(0));\n-      ExtAType =      │
│ GetExtendKind(RedPhiOp1R);\n-    } else if (auto Widen =                                   │
│ dyn_cast<VPWidenRecipe>(RedPhiOp1R))\n-      HandleWiden(Widen);\n+    if (RedPhiOp1R)     │
│ {\n+      if (isa<VPWidenCastRecipe>(RedPhiOp1R)) {\n+        InputTypeA =                 │
│ Ctx.Types.inferScalarType(RedPhiOp1R->getOperand(0));\n+        ExtAType =                 │
│ GetExtendKind(RedPhiOp1R);\n+      } else if (auto Widen =                                 │
│ dyn_cast<VPWidenRecipe>(RedPhiOp1R))\n+        HandleWiden(Widen);\n+    }\n   } else if   │
│ (auto Widen = dyn_cast<VPWidenRecipe>(OpR)) {\n     HandleWiden(Widen);\n   } else if      │
│ (auto Reduction = dyn_cast<VPPartialReductionRecipe>(OpR)) {\n\n```\n\n### 5.              │
│ Conclusion\n\nBy adding a null check for the defining recipe of the reduction's binary     │
│ operator operand, we prevent the crash. This makes the cost model correctly handle         │
│ reductions with loop-invariant scalar operands, which is a valid and common scenario. This │
│ fix will resolve the assertion failure and allow the vectorizer to proceed with cost       │
│ modeling and vectorization."})                                                             │
