│ An analysis of the bug report indicates a crash within the loop vectorizer's cost model,   │
│ specifically in `VPPartialReductionRecipe::computeCost`. The crash is an assertion failure │
│ (`isa<> used on a null pointer`) triggered when analyzing a reduction operation.           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is that the cost model does not correctly handle reductions where one of    │
│ the operands is a loop-invariant value. In the provided reproducer, the reduction is `add  │
│ nsw i32 %rdx, %conv1`. The value `%conv1` is defined outside the loop. When the vectorizer │
│ builds its internal representation (VPlan), this loop-invariant value does not have a      │
│ "defining recipe" within the VPlan's loop body.                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `VPPartialReductionRecipe::computeCost` function attempts to retrieve the defining     │
│ recipe for `%conv1` via `getDefiningRecipe()`, which correctly returns `nullptr`. However, │
│ the subsequent code immediately uses this null pointer in an `isa<>` check, leading to the │
│ assertion and crash.                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a null check. If the defining recipe for an operand is null, it          │
│ signifies a loop-invariant scalar, which requires no special cost calculation in this      │
│ context. By wrapping the logic that inspects the recipe in a null check, we make the cost  │
│ model robust to this valid scenario.                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                                 │
